		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Becoming a Knight, a Paladins Journey</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:khengiskhan@hotmail.com">Edward Redmond</a> | 
		            3/21/2001 9:22:17 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Hail fellow Paladins,<BR>
<BR>
This guide is only meant as a &quot;guide&quot; and not the only way to become a powerful knight and protector of the good.  <BR>
<BR>
This guide is not about what race you should be, that is your choice.  I chose a human paladin, and I began my training in Freeport.  Understand that like all new players, you will have nothing, but that's how we all started.  Begin by hunting small creatures around the city, it may be boring, but keep it up and you will quickly begin leveling up.  For those of you who choose to roleplay, meaning you have decided to act like a paladin would act, understand that most people do not.  A true paladin is the protector of good and would never simply kill for pleasure.  That being said, you must kill to level up, so you choose what you decide to do.  <BR>
Stay close to safety until you level up and the creatures you are hunting no longer give you experience, but don't rush things.  You will eventually adventure to new places, but danger lies ahead, so do not be a hero.  Again with this being said, you will be killed, everyone is killed, usually many times.  Know where you are at all times, and use /loc when you do not know, you will find your corpse much easier.  <BR>
SOW is Spirit of Wolf, ask for it only when you need it, and you will run much faster to regain your possessions.  Really this goes for all classes, but more specifically, a Paladin is different because you are a hybrid class.  A paladin will not level as fast as a warrior, because you are not one.  A paladin is a tank, a tank, for very new players, is the best pure fighter of a group.  A warrior makes the best tank, but Paladins are right behind them.<BR>
As you level up higher, you will have training points to use, do not waste them my Paladin friends.  If you are very new, you don't know where to go to train, I realize that because I didn't know either.  In Freeport you go to the Hall of Truth in North Freeport, and then go upstairs tot he roof, the paladin trainers are there.  If you are in Quenoyes, go to south Q. and the paladin guild is there.<BR>
Bash is a very important skill, learn it and then buy a shield and train it constantly.  Bash will become a great advantage in fighting.  It is the Rangers version of kick, and you will begin to pile up the damage points on your adversary.  Do not just train with one weapon, use all kinds, because you never know what kind of weapon you may use the most.  When you are just starting, and are fortunate to get a second weapon, like a mace, use it, someday you may use a magical mace to smash the undead.<BR>
Your growth to level 9 will be tedious, but have heart fellow paladin, at level 9 things will change.  As for leveling up, and where to hunt, that is up to you.  Depending on where you are, stay where you have a fighting chance by yourself, do not depend on others all the time.  Grouping is a great way to level up, but you can do it alone, it's just not as quick.  In the Freeport area, the ruins are a good spot for you, but be careful there, you can take a skeleton or a rattlesnake, but do not try to fight a ghoul or an asp.<BR>
Remember to /con before you charge, and look before you leap.  No one likes a new player to run away and &quot;train&quot; a bunch of skeletons or ghouls where people are resting and healing.  You will not be a favorite of many, and friends help, more than you know.<BR>
<BR>
With everything being said, and most of this is for any new player, a Paladin will change roles after level 9.  Now you have basic spells, but they are not useless by any means. First of all, you must train one point in every casting category, then purchase the spells you want.  Once you have learned them my friends, you become much more important to people looking for members of a group.  Cast your spells constantly, even on those you do not know who are injured.  This way you are making friends, and learning your spells<BR>
at the sane time.  All remember a Paladin is a good guy, if you have no desire to help others and simply want to kill, be a warrior instead.  A true paladin will always help those in need, always.  If someone calls for help, help then anyway you can.  If you have learned heal, then you are making a great impression by helping them out of there jam, and then healing them.  Your minor heal does not completely heal the person, but you will heal them enough for them to be very grateful.<BR>
I don't think I have mentioned Lay Hands yet, which fellow Paladin, is a tremendous gift.  You will heal yourself or another completely.  You can feel brave knowing that if you must fight a tough creature, lay hands will be there to save you.  It is simply one of the best things you have as a Paladin.  Use it wisely.  Courage is another basic spell that is always nice to cast on you and your party.  Flash of light and cure poison are also very helpful, and others will thank you for helping them.<BR>
<BR>
So now young Paladin you are somewhere between levels 9 and 14, just short of your next big level 15.  You should now be using bash and dodge and should be perfecting them as you battle.  You should be trying to group now, alone you are alright, but with agroup, you are much more useful.  Yourr role is a secondary tank, next to the warrior, and a healer next to a cleric.  Between battles, heal your friends, and keep them ready for battle, saving lay hands until you really need it.  <BR>
By now you have traveled to find experience, and again depending on where you are, stay within your limits, and find friends.  Getting lost is easy to do, always know where you are.  If you are really lost ask a bard to help you find your corpse.  If you are playing the right way, you should have many friends, and people that will help you if you are lost or need assistance.  If you are in West Karana, join a bandit party, and try to obtain red sashes in battle.  Bring the red sash to a guard named Chesgard (sp?) <BR>
at the paladin guild in S. Q. and he will give you money, exp., and maybe a weapon and shield.  It's a great way to get money and experience.  Places like Black Burrow, which is in Q Hills, can be very crowded, and <BR>
you will more than likely perish there.  If I haven't already said this, if you travel from Freeport to Q., or the other way, for the love of all Paladins, get a bind.  If you receive a bind, you will be restored where you were bound to.  So if you came from Freeport, and are now in Q., get yourself binded, it is a long, long, way to get your corpse if you do not.  <BR>
<BR>
By level 12 os so, you should know your role as a Paladin.  You are fairly powerful now, and can solo if you have to.  Here are some things to keep in mind as you gain levels:<BR>
<BR>
1. A paladin is different from a warrior, you are not the best fighter, but a very good one.<BR>
2. Train one point in every thing and then practice, you will implove quickly.<BR>
3. You will not regret it if you act like a paladin.  Be courteous and giving to others, you will make friends, and friends are everything.<BR>
4. Once you hit level 9, learn your spells and practice them.  They are somewhat weak, but can be extremely helpful in a jam.<BR>
5. Try to group and level that way. A paladin is better suited for group work, especially when you can begin to heal your partners.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
There is so much to this adventure it's hard to cover all the bases.  I hope this helps even a little, send me a tell if you need help, I will help anyway I can.<BR>
<BR>
Safe paths my Paladin brothers<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Ellassar, Knight of the 12th Season<BR>
Vazaelle<BR>

